content.problemStatement:
- In C++, default arguments allow functions to use predefined values for parameters if the caller doesn’t provide them. This reduces the need for overloaded functions and provides more flexibility.
- Default arguments must be placed from right to left. That is, if a function has multiple parameters, the ones with default values must be on the rightmost side. **Otherwise, the compiler will raise an error.**

**Syntax:**

```cpp
returnType functionName(parameter1 = defaultValue1, parameter2 = defaultValue2, ...) {
    // Function body
}
```
- **`parameter = defaultValue`**: Sets a default value for the parameter.

---
**Example:**

```cpp
#include 
using namespace std;

// Correct function: default parameter is at the rightmost position
void greetCorrect(string name, string timeOfDay = "morning") {
    cout << "Good " << timeOfDay << ", " << name << "!" << endl;
}

// Incorrect function: default parameter is not at the rightmost position (this will cause a compiler error)
void greetIncorrect(string timeOfDay = "morning", string name) {  // Error: default argument must be last
    cout << "Good " << timeOfDay << ", " << name << "!" << endl;
}

int main() {
    // Correct function calls
    greetCorrect("John");         // Uses the default time of day "morning"
    greetCorrect("Max", "afternoon");  // Specifies "afternoon" instead of the default

    // Incorrect function call (this will cause a compile-time error)
    // greetIncorrect("John");    // Uncommenting this will cause an error because default argument isn't last
    // greetIncorrect("Max", "afternoon"); // This also causes an error

    return 0;
}

```

**Expected Output:**

```default
Good morning, John!
Good afternoon, Max!
```

